 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  has argued</a> that=C2=A0<em>those=C2=
=A0</em>accounts are investment contracts, but that doesn=E2=80=99t make th=
e stablecoin itself a security.)</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">My view is that a stablecoin is probably not a=
 security and the SEC is wrong about BUSD, but I don=E2=80=99t hold that vi=
ew strongly. I do think, however, that if BUSD=C2=A0<em>is=C2=A0</em>a secu=
rity, it=E2=80=99s not because it=E2=80=99s an =E2=80=9Cinvestment contract=
.=E2=80=9D Look at the list of securities.=C2=A0Is a stablecoin =E2=80=9Cev=
idence of indebtedness,=E2=80=9D or a =E2=80=9Cnote=E2=80=9D? I mean, kind =
of? The stablecoin issuer=E2=80=99s promise to redeem the stablecoin for $1=
 is=C2=A0not quite the same sort of legally binding promise you=E2=80=99d f=
ind in a bond debenture, but at the same time stablecoin investors=C2=A0<em=
>obviously=C2=A0</em>expect the thing to be redeemable at least in some ind=
irect way; if investors didn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0<em>treat=C2=A0</em>the stablec=
oin as debt then it wouldn=E2=80=99t work. And =E2=80=9Cevidence of indebte=
dness,=E2=80=9D marketed broadly to retail investors, is a security.<a clas=
s=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-dec=
oration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0=
